01:32.409 --> 01:35.319
Narrator:
In cape cod, massachusetts,

01:35.412 --> 01:39.005
Rick lagina and new England
native matty blake

01:39.100 --> 01:42.826
Join diver tony sampson for
a new and exciting adventure.

01:42.919 --> 01:45.162
They are on their way
to meet tony's friends,

01:45.180 --> 01:49.441
Renowned salvage divers
barry and brandon clifford,

01:49.593 --> 01:51.001
To assist
in their ongoing efforts

01:51.094 --> 01:53.353
Of recovering artifacts
and valuables

01:53.447 --> 01:56.523
Connected to the legendary
18th century pirate wreck

01:56.617 --> 01:58.283
Known as the<i> whydah.</i>

01:58.435 --> 02:00.360
Tony, I want to thank you.

02:00.454 --> 02:02.770
I'm sure matty does, too,
for setting this up.

02:02.865 --> 02:04.181
Well, thanks, guys.

02:04.274 --> 02:06.350
I mean I'm just so happy
you're down here.

02:06.368 --> 02:09.444
And, you know,
in my selfish little mind,

02:09.538 --> 02:12.947
I-I'm just fizzing
at the opportunity

02:13.041 --> 02:15.116
To-to dive the<i> whydah</i> as well.

02:15.136 --> 02:18.545
Matty:
This wreck, the<i> whydah,</i>
is so iconic,

02:18.639 --> 02:22.048
And this team's already
pulled up a lot of artifacts,

02:22.143 --> 02:23.958
So that's always exciting, too,
when you know

02:24.052 --> 02:26.294
That they've done it before.

02:26.313 --> 02:28.129
There's precedent here,
we're gonna see something.

02:28.223 --> 02:29.539
Tony:
Definitely, matty.

02:29.558 --> 02:31.483
I really love this story.

02:31.710 --> 02:34.211
You know, I read
barry clifford's book years ago

02:34.304 --> 02:36.989
On the details
of recovering the<i> whydah,</i>

02:37.216 --> 02:39.733
And the whole story
of the captain of the ship,

02:39.885 --> 02:41.326
"black sam" bellamy.

02:41.553 --> 02:42.494
Yeah, I think we're gonna
learn a lot of things.

02:44.072 --> 02:47.557
Narrator:
During the golden age of piracy
in the americas,

02:47.651 --> 02:51.319
Which took place
from 1650 to 1726,

02:51.338 --> 02:54.489
Black sam bellamy, an englishman

02:54.508 --> 02:56.750
Known for
his dark, flowing hair,

02:56.844 --> 03:00.737
Was one of the most notorious
buccaneers on the high seas.

03:00.756 --> 03:02.406
Simon:
Samuel bellamy became

03:02.499 --> 03:03.849
One of the most successful
pirates of the time.

03:04.076 --> 03:07.168
He would capture
over 50 ships in his career.

03:07.262 --> 03:08.854
One of the big trends of piracy

03:09.005 --> 03:11.690
That the pirate
samuel bellamy started

03:11.841 --> 03:15.343
Was defeating their victims
through intimidation,

03:15.437 --> 03:17.754
Rather than actually
killing people.

03:17.847 --> 03:20.515
He and his men
would charge onto ships

03:20.534 --> 03:22.926
Completely naked
brandishing their weapons.

03:22.945 --> 03:25.037
And people would be
so shocked by this,

03:25.264 --> 03:27.539
That they would surrender
almost immediately.

03:28.617 --> 03:32.544
Narrator:
In early 1717,
black sam bellamy

03:32.696 --> 03:35.530
Made his greatest conquest
when he and his crew

03:35.624 --> 03:39.200
Commandeered the english slave
ship known as the<i> whydah gally.</i>

03:39.294 --> 03:41.778
Simon:
The<i> whydah</i> was the most
powerful and the wealthiest

03:41.797 --> 03:44.056
Of all slaving ships to sail

03:44.207 --> 03:45.474
Throughout the world
at that time.

03:47.953 --> 03:51.788
It was 110 feet long
and weighed about 300 tons.

03:51.807 --> 03:54.124
Along with all the goods
that the<i> whydah</i> contained,

03:54.217 --> 03:57.218
It also had gold
and silver packed away

03:57.312 --> 03:59.646
In 50-pound bags
all throughout the ship.

03:59.798 --> 04:04.301
Narrator:
The<i> whydah</i> was also carrying
approximately 50 african slaves,

04:04.319 --> 04:07.895
Whom captain bellamy
immediately emancipated.

04:07.915 --> 04:11.250
He also offered them
membership on his crew

04:11.401 --> 04:13.994
With equal shares
of compensation

04:14.146 --> 04:16.255
And voting rights
regarding operations.

04:16.406 --> 04:18.648
They all accepted.

04:18.667 --> 04:21.835
Simon:
Black sam bellamy was known
as the robin hood of the sea,

04:21.929 --> 04:24.671
And this is because he really
made a huge effort to make sure

04:24.823 --> 04:26.840
That every single person
in his crew

04:26.934 --> 04:28.508
Very much got their equal share.

04:28.660 --> 04:29.768
Not just people in the crew,

04:29.919 --> 04:32.178
But even people
that he captured.

04:32.273 --> 04:34.273
He-he wanted to make sure
that they were treated well

04:34.424 --> 04:35.357
And would get their share.

04:37.336 --> 04:39.111
Narrator:
As the captain of the<i> whydah,</i>

04:39.338 --> 04:43.115
Black sam bellamy made his
way north toward massachusetts

04:43.342 --> 04:45.933
Plundering an astounding
54 additional merchant

04:46.028 --> 04:48.120
And pirate ships along the way.

04:48.271 --> 04:52.440
Simon:
It is estimated that the<i> whydah</i>
carried five tons of gold,

04:52.534 --> 04:54.534
Silver and various jewels,

04:54.628 --> 04:56.110
Making black sam bellamy

04:56.130 --> 04:58.855
Probably the wealthiest
pirate in history.

04:58.874 --> 05:01.374
Narrator:
But as the<i> whydah</i>
approached cape cod

05:01.527 --> 05:05.804
On April 26, 1717,
tragedy struck

05:06.031 --> 05:09.957
As a violent nor'easter
devastated the ship.

05:10.052 --> 05:13.645
Simon:
The<i> whydah</i> ended up crashing
onto the coastline of cape cod.

05:13.797 --> 05:17.541
Almost immediately,
the ship completely capsized,

05:17.634 --> 05:19.467
Because it broke
into loads of pieces.

05:19.486 --> 05:21.711
When it broke into
all these pieces,

05:21.730 --> 05:23.897
Many of the pirates on the ship

05:23.991 --> 05:25.640
Were either killed instantly,

05:25.659 --> 05:27.551
Or they were severely injured,
and drowned.

05:27.569 --> 05:32.072
All but two of the<i> whydah's</i>
146-man crew

05:32.166 --> 05:36.335
Perished in the disaster,
including black sam himself.

05:37.563 --> 05:39.896
The scattered remains
of the ship

05:39.989 --> 05:42.065
Sank in the waters
off of cape cod

05:42.158 --> 05:45.569
And would be lost
for more than two centuries

05:45.587 --> 05:49.514
Until explorer barry clifford
and his team discovered them.

05:49.666 --> 05:53.000
Matty:
I'm excited, guys. And I think
we're coming up on it.

05:53.020 --> 05:56.246
Yep, this is the research center
here, right on the left, mate.

05:56.264 --> 06:00.083
Matty:
This one is very special
for me, this adventure,

06:00.176 --> 06:03.010
Because I'm about to meet
two legends around here,

06:03.105 --> 06:04.754
Barry and brandon clifford.

06:04.773 --> 06:06.347
Growing up around here,

06:06.367 --> 06:08.349
It's hard not to hear
about the<i> whydah,</i>

06:08.369 --> 06:10.093
But I didn't know the details,

06:10.186 --> 06:12.019
And I'm really looking forward
to meeting them.

06:12.039 --> 06:14.689
Good morning, guys.
Good to see you again, barry.

06:14.708 --> 06:16.375
Hey. Good morning. How are
you there, young fella?

06:16.602 --> 06:18.377
-Good to see you again, brandon.
-Hey tony, nice to see you.

06:18.604 --> 06:19.861
Rick:
Barry clifford
and his son brandon

06:19.955 --> 06:21.713
Have committed
literally their lives

06:21.940 --> 06:24.365
To this endeavor
and they're not here

06:24.385 --> 06:26.776
Just because there's
treasure on the seafloor.

06:26.870 --> 06:28.536
They're here
to retrieve that story

06:28.555 --> 06:30.204
Which has been lost for so long.

06:30.224 --> 06:31.723
That's inspirational.

06:31.875 --> 06:33.558
-Barry.
-Barry: Howdy.

06:33.785 --> 06:35.135
That gentleman speaks highly
of both of you.

06:35.287 --> 06:36.119
Wow.

06:36.212 --> 06:38.230
Most impressed to meet you, sir.

06:38.381 --> 06:39.956
-How much did he pay you?
-I told li... I told lies.

06:40.049 --> 06:42.292
(laughter)

06:42.385 --> 06:43.977
Barry:
I'm barry clifford,
I'm an explorer.

06:44.071 --> 06:45.386
I grew up on the cape,

06:45.480 --> 06:46.963
So, it was always, you know,

06:47.056 --> 06:49.390
Exploring,
looking for things, and

06:49.410 --> 06:51.801
As a kid, I used to sit around
the old fish shack,

06:51.895 --> 06:54.320
And listen to the stories
they would tell.

06:54.473 --> 06:57.416
And the<i> whydah</i> was a story that
sort of resonated in my mind.

06:57.567 --> 06:59.492
Brandon:
I'm brandon clifford.

06:59.586 --> 07:01.995
The<i> whydah</i> was really
a folktale on the cape

07:02.089 --> 07:04.648
That had become this, like, myth

07:04.741 --> 07:06.240
And, you know, there were
stories of coins

07:06.334 --> 07:07.575
That washed up on the beach.

07:07.669 --> 07:09.486
And my dad was a cape codder

07:09.579 --> 07:10.987
And he heard all these stories

07:11.080 --> 07:13.173
And it inspired him
to go search.

07:13.267 --> 07:16.601
Narrator:
In 1982, barry,

07:16.753 --> 07:20.772
Along with his friend and fellow
adventurer john f. Kennedy jr.,

07:20.924 --> 07:23.667
Discovered a survey map
of the original wreck site

07:23.760 --> 07:28.447
Created in 1718 by cartographer
cyprian southack,

07:28.598 --> 07:31.508
And began a quest
to bring the story of black sam

07:31.526 --> 07:34.027
And the<i> whydah</i> back to life.

07:34.121 --> 07:38.606
Barry:
In '85, we discovered
this large concretion

07:38.700 --> 07:41.685
With what appeared to be a bell
sticking out of the side of it.

07:41.703 --> 07:43.444
We brought it back
to our laboratory,

07:43.464 --> 07:46.039
The letter "w" pops up
and then "h"

07:46.133 --> 07:49.968
And the y-d-a-h. 1716.

07:50.119 --> 07:53.379
It said
"the whydah gally, 1716."

07:53.474 --> 07:55.289
So, then that was the front
page of<i> the new york times.</i>

07:55.383 --> 07:57.458
My phone never stopped ringing.

07:57.552 --> 08:02.463
Narrator:
Ever since that fateful
discovery in 1985,

08:02.557 --> 08:05.650
Barry clifford obtained
the exclusive salvage rights

08:05.802 --> 08:08.970
To the<i> whydah's</i> wreckage and has
continued recovering artifacts

08:08.989 --> 08:12.065
And valuables in the waters
off cape cod.

08:12.159 --> 08:16.402
Although john f. Kennedy jr.,
along with his wife carolyn,

08:16.555 --> 08:21.649
Tragically passed away in 1999,
barry's son brandon

08:21.668 --> 08:24.652
Works tirelessly beside him
in the effort.

08:24.671 --> 08:27.339
To date, they have found
more than

08:27.490 --> 08:31.751
100,000 artifacts, valuables
and even human remains

08:31.903 --> 08:33.595
Related to the<i> whydah.</i>

08:34.497 --> 08:35.572
This is great.

08:35.590 --> 08:36.848
So, uh, is this the lab

08:37.000 --> 08:38.575
And where you kind of
take care of

08:38.668 --> 08:40.334
The items that you bring up
from the<i> whydah?</i>

08:40.428 --> 08:42.078
-Yes.
-Brandon: Yep, that's correct.

08:42.097 --> 08:43.688
So, we recover material
from the<i> whydah</i>

08:43.915 --> 08:46.024
And it's brought back here
where our conservators

08:46.251 --> 08:49.769
-Then put it through
a process of conservation.
-Wow.

08:49.863 --> 08:53.089
And then we have two museums and
we're building a third museum

08:53.108 --> 08:55.182
And that's the essence
of what we do.

08:55.277 --> 08:57.093
We display the artifacts
that we bring up

08:57.112 --> 08:58.778
For educational purposes.

08:58.872 --> 09:00.446
And we've kept the entire
collection together.

09:00.599 --> 09:01.781
We don't sell anything.

09:01.875 --> 09:03.875
That's incredible.

09:04.027 --> 09:05.952
-So, are we allowed
to see some of this stuff?
-Absolutely.

09:06.046 --> 09:07.546
You should come back here
and have a look at some of this.

09:07.697 --> 09:10.106
Let's see it.

09:10.199 --> 09:11.941
Wow, this is fantastic, guys.

09:12.035 --> 09:14.444
I love the array of cannon
right there.

09:14.537 --> 09:16.296
-Matty: Oh, no way.
-Rick: Beautiful.

09:16.448 --> 09:18.557
Tony:
So, what was it?
62 cannon you pulled off this?

09:18.784 --> 09:20.392
We found 61.

09:20.619 --> 09:22.802
-61?
-Yeah, we've brought
up 50, I think.

09:22.896 --> 09:24.470
-Wow.
-Wow.

09:24.623 --> 09:26.639
-There's 11 still
buried offshore.
-Incredible.

09:26.733 --> 09:30.718
Barry:
Some of these cannons
were antiques in 1717.

09:30.812 --> 09:32.128
-Matty: Wow.
-Tony: Wow.

09:32.221 --> 09:33.630
This is the way you
see them now,

09:33.648 --> 09:35.890
But this cannon right here,
for example,

09:35.984 --> 09:38.968
This is what cannons look
like when we first find them.

09:38.987 --> 09:42.155
In this one, you can see it has
a gun door from the ship

09:42.249 --> 09:44.657
Still concreted to the cannon

09:44.810 --> 09:47.752
With a variety
of other artifacts

09:47.904 --> 09:50.163
All fused into the cannon.

09:50.315 --> 09:52.424
And that's what a concretion
looks like.

09:52.651 --> 09:55.985
Narrator:
Concretions are hardened
conglomerations

09:56.079 --> 09:59.080
Created over time
when iron artifacts corrode

09:59.099 --> 10:02.175
In salt water
and collect nearby objects.

10:02.269 --> 10:05.086
Should we go discuss the
dive plan in the meeting room?

10:05.180 --> 10:06.012
-Yeah.
-Sounds fantastic.

10:06.106 --> 10:07.254
I would love that.

10:07.349 --> 10:09.924
Matty:
This is incredible, guys.

10:09.943 --> 10:12.277
We're going over
the dive plan now,

10:12.504 --> 10:15.839
Uh, we're all anxious to get
out there and see this treasure.

10:15.932 --> 10:17.115
We want to see treasure,
we want to see artifacts,

10:17.266 --> 10:18.842
And that's why we're here.

10:18.935 --> 10:20.785
You know, we can actually
see some of this surface

10:21.012 --> 10:24.180
For the first time ever since
it went down in the 1700s.

10:24.199 --> 10:26.791
These are some of the coins
that we've found

10:27.018 --> 10:30.778
And, um, a stack of them,
eight reales.

10:30.797 --> 10:33.539
They're all
in pretty good condition.

10:33.692 --> 10:34.949
They called it a sock roll.

10:34.968 --> 10:36.526
They'd roll them up
in a sock, like a wallet.

10:36.544 --> 10:37.302
-Rick: Wow.
-Matty: Perfect, yeah, yeah.

10:38.880 --> 10:39.879
Wow.

10:41.216 --> 10:45.793
Matty:
You know, when I see this,
I can't help but think of value.

10:45.887 --> 10:47.370
And I just want to be clear,

10:47.463 --> 10:49.372
That's not what drives us,
but I mean,

10:49.391 --> 10:51.483
Coins equals treasure in a way.

10:51.634 --> 10:54.819
And so, what you've collected
so far,

10:54.971 --> 10:56.804
Your vast collection that
some people have estimated

10:56.898 --> 10:59.306
It might be worth $400 million.

10:59.401 --> 11:00.733
What do you think of that?

11:00.827 --> 11:02.309
I have no idea.

11:02.404 --> 11:03.720
You don't context it like that?

11:03.813 --> 11:05.405
I don't think of it
like that, no.

11:05.499 --> 11:08.315
I mean, I know that
<i> the wall street journal</i>

11:08.410 --> 11:10.651
And some of the other people

11:10.745 --> 11:12.820
Estimated it be worth
$400 million.

11:12.839 --> 11:14.839
Um, and that was 40 years ago.

11:15.066 --> 11:16.490
Mm-hmm.

11:16.510 --> 11:20.011
In terms of the-the
so-called mother lode,

11:20.163 --> 11:21.254
We haven't found that yet.

11:21.406 --> 11:22.238
Wow.

11:22.331 --> 11:24.832
So, we'll probably pick up right

11:24.851 --> 11:26.743
Where we left off last season.

11:26.836 --> 11:29.854
Go back to the same location
towards the beach.

11:30.081 --> 11:32.932
We've located a new cannon,
a small cannon,

11:33.026 --> 11:36.027
Uh, that we believe was kept
on the stern of the<i> whydah.</i>

11:36.179 --> 11:38.530
-We believe we-we're on
the trail of the stern.
-Oh, wow.

11:38.757 --> 11:40.440
Brandon:
The stern section is, you know,

11:40.592 --> 11:41.925
Where the captain's quarters

11:42.018 --> 11:43.702
And the officer quarters
would've been.

11:43.929 --> 11:46.112
And if we're able to find
the area where

11:46.264 --> 11:48.540
That section
of the wreck rested,

11:48.767 --> 11:51.451
You would find
significant artifacts.

11:51.545 --> 11:54.361
Things that bellamy had,
himself, in his cabin.

11:54.381 --> 11:56.864
So, weather provided,

11:56.883 --> 11:59.384
We'll head out the inlet
and head up the cape coast

11:59.535 --> 12:02.887
To the<i> whydah</i> site, inshore from
the main point of the shipwreck.

12:03.114 --> 12:05.706
Then we'll, uh, set up
our grids under water

12:05.726 --> 12:08.284
With the assistance
of tony, and we'll go to work.

12:08.377 --> 12:10.620
All right, well,
as we've said before,

12:10.713 --> 12:12.121
Talk is wonderful,
but let's get going.

12:12.215 --> 12:14.215
-Let's get out there.
-Fantastic.

12:14.234 --> 12:16.192
-It's the only way things
get done, right?
-That's right.

12:23.910 --> 12:26.060
Matty: I love dive day, captain.

12:26.079 --> 12:27.746
Now, where are we going exactly?

12:27.897 --> 12:32.083
We are going through
east orleans here,

12:32.235 --> 12:35.144
Up north to the<i> whydah</i> site.
Marconi beach.

