Rick lagina and matty blake
are being transported

12:41.410 --> 12:42.910
To the<i> whydah</i> search area

12:42.929 --> 12:44.837
By captain jeff spiegel,

12:44.990 --> 12:47.248
Who has been working
with barry and brandon clifford

12:47.267 --> 12:49.917
To salvage valuables
related to the<i> whydah</i>

12:50.011 --> 12:51.919
For more than 30 years.

12:51.938 --> 12:54.497
We're excited to get back to it.

12:54.516 --> 12:56.516
-We always are.
-I love it.

12:56.668 --> 12:57.567
Rick:
We're ready.

13:00.947 --> 13:02.855
Rick:
We've all got
our fingers crossed.

13:03.008 --> 13:04.932
I'm hoping to find
something unique today.

13:04.951 --> 13:07.601
Something that tells a story.

13:07.621 --> 13:10.455
We're gonna find treasure,
that's the hope.

13:13.701 --> 13:15.609
-Tony: See, look at this here.
-(seagulls screeching)

13:15.629 --> 13:17.295
That's kind of interesting, huh?

13:17.446 --> 13:19.038
Narrator:
Meanwhile...

13:19.190 --> 13:21.541
Tony sampson
and brandon clifford

13:21.635 --> 13:25.452
Have begun a side scan
sonar survey of the target area

13:25.472 --> 13:28.973
In the hopes of identifying
signs of the<i> whydah's</i> stern

13:29.125 --> 13:33.478
And the vast cache of valuables
it is believed to contain.

13:33.629 --> 13:35.538
Should we try and give it
a shot east/west

13:35.557 --> 13:36.773
-And just see what we
come up with there?
-Sure.

13:39.486 --> 13:42.562
Narrator:
The humminbird helix 10
sonar device

13:42.714 --> 13:44.897
Emits high-frequency
sound pulses

13:44.991 --> 13:47.717
That reflect off the ocean floor

13:47.810 --> 13:49.828
To produce an image
of the bottom,

13:49.979 --> 13:53.556
As well as any potential
structures, or objects,

13:53.649 --> 13:56.075
That may not be
natural features.

13:56.227 --> 13:59.838
Tony:
So, what we're doing,
we call it lawn mowing.

13:59.989 --> 14:02.065
So, you're literally going
up and back in lines,

14:02.083 --> 14:03.091
Like lawn mowing.

14:04.569 --> 14:06.235
The side scan, what it does,

14:06.254 --> 14:09.013
Is it looks down
and out to the side

14:09.165 --> 14:11.257
And you can actually
see the height of the structure

14:11.351 --> 14:15.578
Off the bottom as well, and
any shadows that it puts out.

14:15.671 --> 14:18.339
So, in a perfect world here
you might see, um,

14:18.433 --> 14:21.084
A timber structure or maybe
something like an anchor

14:21.177 --> 14:22.485
Protruding from the bottom.

14:23.438 --> 14:25.254
Brandon:
Fortunately, this spot

14:25.273 --> 14:27.532
Is uncovered from sand
and we're getting some

14:27.683 --> 14:31.202
Pretty, pretty nice images
with our side scan.

14:31.429 --> 14:35.781
Narrator:
While tony and brandon continue
their side-scan sonar survey...

14:35.876 --> 14:37.876
Matty: Barry!

14:38.103 --> 14:40.694
Good to see you again,
my friend.

14:40.714 --> 14:44.048
Narrator:
...Captain jeff, rick and matty
arrive at the search area

14:44.200 --> 14:46.700
Where they rejoin
barry clifford.

14:46.720 --> 14:48.136
Rick:
All right, barry's on board.

14:50.115 --> 14:51.038
Matty:
My friend.

14:51.057 --> 14:52.557
Barry:
How are you?

14:52.784 --> 14:53.950
Well, it's good to see you
on the water.

14:53.968 --> 14:55.042
I think this is your
natural habitat.

14:55.061 --> 14:56.895
Been here a long time.

14:57.046 --> 14:58.879
-Matty: Yes, sir.
-Almost 40 years.

14:58.973 --> 15:00.732
I see your son is over here.

15:00.883 --> 15:03.234
What's the... What's the
dive plan today with him?

15:03.386 --> 15:05.645
We're essentially
following artifacts

15:05.797 --> 15:07.906
That we found before

15:08.133 --> 15:09.556
And we believe are
leading to the stern.

15:09.651 --> 15:12.301
-Ooh.
-So, all of the valuables

15:12.320 --> 15:15.821
That they stole from the
54 ships that they captured,

15:15.916 --> 15:17.657
Were supposedly in this area.

15:17.809 --> 15:19.659
Wow.

15:21.087 --> 15:23.421
Narrator:
While tony and brandon
gather the data needed

15:23.572 --> 15:27.166
To dive on the wreck of the
<i> whydah</i> from their boat,

15:27.318 --> 15:31.745
Rick, matty and barry clifford
are monitoring the operation

15:31.765 --> 15:34.507
From their own boat
less than 100 yards away.

15:34.659 --> 15:36.159
Look how linear this is.

15:36.177 --> 15:38.995
-Mm-hmm.
-That's kind of weird, huh?

15:39.013 --> 15:41.105
I mean,
that is unbelievably linear.

15:41.332 --> 15:43.683
Brandon:
You know,
maybe a cannon possibly.

15:43.835 --> 15:45.685
Tony:
Yeah. Like, that's what
I think, yeah.

15:45.837 --> 15:47.853
On the side scan,
when we're looking at it,

15:48.006 --> 15:49.263
We're actually seeing

15:49.282 --> 15:51.190
An artifact that looks
like cannon.

15:51.342 --> 15:53.176
Our heartrates are going up

15:53.194 --> 15:54.935
And we're getting excited

15:55.029 --> 15:56.788
Seeing this sort of stuff
on the bottom.

15:56.939 --> 16:00.208
Brandon:
Yeah, this is
a good area to dive.

16:01.944 --> 16:03.211
Brandon:
Boat one to boat two?

16:04.372 --> 16:05.964
Yeah, copy that,
you're loud and clear.

16:06.115 --> 16:08.024
We're gonna set up
and we're gonna head inshore

16:08.117 --> 16:11.118
To this wreckage
that we're looking at

16:11.137 --> 16:13.287
And make a couple dives on it.

16:13.381 --> 16:16.199
We scanned the wreck and it
looks pretty interesting.

16:16.217 --> 16:19.978
There are a few shapes
that look like cannon,

16:20.129 --> 16:21.813
With deep shadows.

16:21.964 --> 16:24.798
Pretty interesting,
so, we're excited to go jump it.

16:24.818 --> 16:26.726
Okay, all right, standing by.

16:26.820 --> 16:29.803
Boat two out.

16:29.897 --> 16:31.230
When you hear things like that,

16:31.382 --> 16:31.990
You want to jump
in the water, yourself.

16:32.141 --> 16:33.825
(laughter)

16:33.976 --> 16:35.994
Barry:
This could be a section
of the ship.

16:36.145 --> 16:38.221
And what's happening with
this weather we've been getting,

16:38.239 --> 16:40.072
Are things that
have been getting uncovered.

16:40.166 --> 16:42.166
But who knows?

16:42.318 --> 16:44.651
-That could be
a piece of the<i> whydah.</i>
-Incredible.

16:44.746 --> 16:46.395
All right, well, we have
a comms system, we can stay

16:46.414 --> 16:47.839
In touch with the divers
as they dive here.

16:48.066 --> 16:49.990
So, I'll get the transducer
in the water

16:50.010 --> 16:50.991
And we can monitor
their progress.

16:51.011 --> 16:52.760
Okay.

16:55.406 --> 16:56.848
Matty:
Tony and brandon are just about

16:57.075 --> 16:59.183
To get into the water there
on their dive boat.

16:59.410 --> 17:01.410
Barry, rick and myself
will stay topside.

17:01.504 --> 17:04.580
Monitoring comms, stay in
communication with them.

17:04.599 --> 17:07.191
I want success
for barry and brandon,

17:07.343 --> 17:09.843
Not just for them, but also
to kind of represent

17:09.863 --> 17:11.845
What we are here in new England.

17:11.865 --> 17:13.698
You know, we're hard workers,

17:13.849 --> 17:16.275
We love our history,
and we don't stop.

17:16.427 --> 17:18.202
Hopefully, today's the day.

17:21.041 --> 17:23.190
Rick:
Splash one.

17:23.209 --> 17:25.043
Jeff:
Divers in the water.

17:27.047 --> 17:28.621
Matty:
Second diver in.

17:28.773 --> 17:31.274
Tony sampson's in the water.

17:31.292 --> 17:32.884
All right, we have
divers in the water.

17:33.111 --> 17:34.218
Yep.

17:46.232 --> 17:49.317
Comms are here,
we hear you. Over.

17:50.812 --> 17:54.797
Tony:
We splash and the currents
aren't bad at all.

17:54.890 --> 17:58.651
We start to descend down,
the heart drops a little

17:58.803 --> 18:00.970
Because we realize
the visibility

18:00.988 --> 18:04.323
Is around at two feet
to three feet maximum.

18:04.475 --> 18:06.375
You know, this is all
part of the game.

18:14.001 --> 18:16.427
Brandon:
Diving on the<i> whydah</i>
is very technical.

18:16.579 --> 18:17.929
You know, we depend heavily
on safety, you know,

18:18.080 --> 18:19.746
And-and-technique.

18:19.766 --> 18:22.749
We deal with an ever-changing
climate down there.

18:22.769 --> 18:24.268
And when you're working
with other divers,

18:24.420 --> 18:26.253
You're really depending
on each other to be there

18:26.347 --> 18:28.106
And to be able
to support each other.

18:39.677 --> 18:41.510
Ooh.

18:41.529 --> 18:45.206
Repeat. Did you say on target?
Confirm. Over.

19:01.215 --> 19:03.215
Matty:
We like to hear that, brandon.

19:03.309 --> 19:06.310
Do you have your metal detector
with you, tony? Over.

19:08.815 --> 19:09.981
(beeping)

19:14.470 --> 19:15.895
(detector beeping)

19:15.989 --> 19:17.380
Matty:
Love it.

19:17.398 --> 19:18.656
Sing, baby, sing.

19:32.338 --> 19:34.255
Love it. Sing, baby, sing. Over.

19:37.735 --> 19:41.737
Narrator:
Just off the coast
of cape cod, massachusetts,

19:41.756 --> 19:44.831
Divers tony sampson
and brandon clifford

19:44.851 --> 19:46.350
Have just found
possible evidence

19:46.577 --> 19:50.504
Of a portion of the legendary
<i> wydah gally,</i>

19:50.523 --> 19:54.025
Captained by the notorious
pirate black sam bellamy.

19:54.176 --> 19:56.435
The<i> whydah</i> broke apart

19:56.529 --> 20:00.439
And sank in a violent nor'easter
back in 1717,

20:00.591 --> 20:03.284
Along with a massive fortune
in treasure.

20:10.359 --> 20:11.709
Matty:
Sounds good. Any way to tell

20:11.860 --> 20:13.936
What size timers they are,

20:14.029 --> 20:15.838
How big are the timbers? Over.

20:28.043 --> 20:30.019
Copy that.

20:48.155 --> 20:50.581
Wow. Nailed it.

20:50.733 --> 20:53.309
Barry:
It's very interesting that
it's a very intact section

20:53.327 --> 20:55.327
Of a wooden ship.

20:55.480 --> 20:57.146
It needs to be investigated.

20:57.164 --> 20:59.090
You know, it's a big section
of the ship.

20:59.317 --> 21:00.758
It definitely could be
part of the<i> whydah.</i>

21:00.985 --> 21:03.427
Now you know definitively
it's not just not a...

21:03.579 --> 21:05.096
Not just an image
on a side scan.

21:05.247 --> 21:07.172
-Barry: Oh, no.
-It's eyes on the target.

21:07.325 --> 21:08.915
Yeah. It's history
no matter what it is.

21:08.935 --> 21:10.417
Absolutely is.

21:10.436 --> 21:13.104
How's the visibility
down there, fellas? Over.

21:19.170 --> 21:22.004
Tony:
Every time we fan the sand,
we're silted out.

21:22.023 --> 21:23.856
And then all of a sudden,

21:24.008 --> 21:27.267
It's like somebody has tipped
a salad bowl on top of us

21:27.361 --> 21:28.935
And you have this mung weed,

21:28.955 --> 21:31.605
It's like lettuce floating
past your mask.

21:31.624 --> 21:33.541
And you are literally
swimming in a salad.

21:45.196 --> 21:47.471
Roger that. We hear you.
Surface is waiting.

21:47.623 --> 21:50.032
Come on up
when you're ready. Over.

21:50.125 --> 21:51.383
Brandon:
You really can't see anything.

21:51.477 --> 21:52.959
So, we really have to back off

21:52.979 --> 21:55.387
And wait until we can work
in clearer water

21:55.540 --> 21:57.039
So we can get all...

21:57.132 --> 21:58.374
Collect all the data
that we could use.

21:58.467 --> 21:59.708
They're coming up.
Right over there.

21:59.802 --> 22:01.727
-Barry: Oh, yep.
-Matty: Got them all.

22:01.821 --> 22:03.729
All the divers are up.

22:03.881 --> 22:06.382
Tony:
I believe what we were seeing
on the side scan

22:06.475 --> 22:08.400
Was these large wooden
structures.

22:08.553 --> 22:10.052
You know, now it looks like

22:10.145 --> 22:11.904
We're following
the yellow brick road.

22:11.998 --> 22:13.889
You sounded happy down there,
like you had a great target.

22:13.908 --> 22:15.741
Tell me about it.

22:15.835 --> 22:18.819
Well, we saw, uh, a lot of big
pieces of old timbers.

22:18.838 --> 22:20.396
The first piece,

22:20.489 --> 22:23.399
We swam upon was
what we think was a spar,

22:23.492 --> 22:24.900
A part of the rigging
on the ship.

22:24.993 --> 22:27.903
A round, beautiful piece
of long wood.

22:27.922 --> 22:30.497
It's definitely within
the vicinity of the<i> whydah.</i>

22:30.591 --> 22:32.165
And that wood
could've been buried for,

22:32.259 --> 22:33.333
You know, hundreds of years

22:33.427 --> 22:35.928
And preserved under sand, so...

22:36.080 --> 22:37.096
Matty:
We're running out
of daylight here,

22:37.190 --> 22:38.839
So let's do it again tomorrow.

22:38.933 --> 22:40.340
Brandon:
Tomorrow, I think we should

22:40.434 --> 22:42.509
Actually move off of this spot.

22:42.603 --> 22:44.269
-Matty: Okay.
-Just because the visibility
is not very good.

22:44.422 --> 22:46.605
And we-we'll head offshore
a little ways

22:46.699 --> 22:49.108
-Where we hope to find
better visibility
-matty: Right.

22:49.260 --> 22:51.702
And pick up on that debris field
that we've been working on.

22:51.929 --> 22:53.779
In the meantime, you guys
should come check out

22:53.873 --> 22:55.948
The whydah pirate museum.
I think you'll really enjoy it.

22:56.042 --> 22:57.449
Matty:
Let's do it.

22:57.602 --> 22:59.043
Okay, everybody, thanks.
Great dive.

23:00.028 --> 23:01.003
Good work.

23:02.106 --> 23:04.106
Narrator:
Later that afternoon...

23:04.199 --> 23:06.032
-So, this is it, huh?
-This is it.

23:06.052 --> 23:07.200
It's awesome.

23:07.294 --> 23:09.111
-Come on in.
-All right.

23:09.130 --> 23:11.037
Narrator:
...Barry and brandon clifford

23:11.132 --> 23:13.707
Welcome matty, rick and tony

23:13.801 --> 23:15.284
To the whydah pirate museum

23:15.302 --> 23:18.044
Located in west yarmouth,
massachusetts.

23:18.139 --> 23:19.805
Matty:
This is cool already.

23:19.957 --> 23:21.957
Wow.

23:22.050 --> 23:24.050
Brandon:
Here you see
the-the<i> whydah's</i> anchor.

23:24.070 --> 23:26.070
Oh, wow.

23:26.297 --> 23:27.146
One of the anchors.

23:27.240 --> 23:29.556
Matty:
My goodness.

23:29.650 --> 23:31.650
Your-your team found this?

23:31.744 --> 23:34.653
Brandon:
We did. We've recovered
three anchors so far.

23:34.747 --> 23:36.305
I mean, it's so pristine,
it's like in perfect shape.

23:36.323 --> 23:37.990
And it speaks to the size
of the ship, too.

23:38.084 --> 23:39.733
That's incredible.

23:39.827 --> 23:41.810
It tells me a couple things.

23:41.904 --> 23:43.495
Number one is the size
of the ship is massive.

23:43.589 --> 23:46.165
The other thing that it tells me
is how violent the storm was.

23:46.259 --> 23:48.150
That is a huge anchor

23:48.169 --> 23:51.262
And this ship got tossed
like a rag doll,

23:51.413 --> 23:53.580
Turned upside-down,
churned and sunk.

23:53.674 --> 23:56.825
We're gonna take you in and show
you some of our concretions now

23:56.919 --> 23:58.327
That our archeologists
are working on.

23:58.345 --> 24:00.253
Let's go.

24:00.273 --> 24:03.182
Narrator:
Established in 2016,

24:03.276 --> 24:07.186
This facility is one of two
museums related to the<i> whydah</i>

24:07.338 --> 24:10.614
That have been founded
by barry clifford.

24:10.766 --> 24:13.692
It houses thousands of artifacts
recovered from the wreck,

24:13.786 --> 24:18.438
Including one concretion that
contains the entire skeleton

24:18.532 --> 24:19.606
Of an unidentified crew member.

24:19.625 --> 24:21.533
Matty:
Oh, man.

24:21.686 --> 24:23.461
Barry:
It's the tomb
of the lost pirate.

24:25.022 --> 24:25.921
No kidding.

24:27.191 --> 24:29.525
Barry:
This is a human skeleton
encapsulated

24:29.543 --> 24:30.709
Within that concretion.

24:30.803 --> 24:32.219
Matty:
Oh, my god.

24:33.380 --> 24:36.098
X-ray machine.
Let me show you. Um...

24:38.219 --> 24:40.385
This is his pelvis.

24:40.538 --> 24:42.387
-Matty: Oh, my god.
-Rick: There he is.

24:42.540 --> 24:43.797
Barry:
And right over his pocket,

24:43.891 --> 24:45.316
Where his pocket would be,

24:45.543 --> 24:47.392
It appears to be a pocket
filled with treasure.

24:47.545 --> 24:49.803
Matty:
Oh, those look like coins.
Yeah, you're right. Wow.

24:49.897 --> 24:52.231
Barry:
And you can see one
of his bones sticking up out...

24:52.325 --> 24:54.566
Matty:
Oh, my god.

24:54.719 --> 24:57.143
Barry:
We brought this up
many, many, many years ago.

24:57.163 --> 24:59.312
And we've kept it together
like this because it...

24:59.332 --> 25:02.074
I think it captures
what things look like

25:02.168 --> 25:04.243
After they've been under
the water for so long.

25:04.337 --> 25:07.246
Brandon:
These concretions we've
recovered, they're essentially

25:07.340 --> 25:08.655
Time capsules, right?

25:08.749 --> 25:10.508
We-we don't know
what's inside them.

25:10.735 --> 25:12.901
And-and the only way you can
find out what's inside them,

25:12.995 --> 25:14.903
The first step is to x-ray it.

25:14.922 --> 25:17.756
After having a good x-ray
of the concretion,

25:17.908 --> 25:20.184
Our conservators are able to

25:20.335 --> 25:22.836
Then approach the artifacts
within the concretion

25:22.855 --> 25:24.838
Using, like, the proper methods.

25:24.857 --> 25:26.749
Barry:
I want to introduce you
to our archeologist,

25:26.842 --> 25:29.509
Andrew, who's in charge
of, uh, de-concreting.

25:29.529 --> 25:30.677
Hey, andrew. Tony.
Nice to meet you.

25:30.696 --> 25:32.421
-Hey, tony.
-Hey, matty blake.

25:32.514 --> 25:33.847
-How are you? Good to meet you.
-Nice to meet you.

25:33.866 --> 25:35.774
All right, if you want
to step this way...

25:35.868 --> 25:37.926
-Oh, yeah.
-...Got a little
surprise for you guys here.

25:37.945 --> 25:39.428
You're gonna like this.

25:39.521 --> 25:41.263
This is a very special
concretion.

25:41.356 --> 25:42.706
We don't find these every day.

25:44.026 --> 25:45.601
-Tony: Oh, look at the coins.
-Rick: Oh, look what I see.

25:45.619 --> 25:47.878
-Matty: Oh! Wow.
-Andrew: You see all the coins?

25:48.105 --> 25:48.862
Andrew:
So, the coins here,
here, here.

25:48.956 --> 25:50.606
And if you look, they go all

25:50.624 --> 25:52.866
The way through the center
to under here.

25:52.960 --> 25:54.443
So, this is a stack of coins

25:54.461 --> 25:55.944
That goes through
the entire concretion

25:55.963 --> 25:57.555
And then boom, right there
in the middle,

25:57.782 --> 26:00.299
You can see that piece
of a gold bar.

26:00.393 --> 26:02.876
-Matty: What?
That's gold all right.
-Andrew: Yeah.

26:02.895 --> 26:04.970
-Matty: Wow. That's gold, baby.
-Andrew: Yeah.

26:05.122 --> 26:06.955
Tony:
That is fantastic.

26:06.974 --> 26:10.734
Barry:
Once we discovered what
we had and the thousands

26:10.961 --> 26:13.312
And thousands of artifacts
that we've brought up,

26:13.406 --> 26:16.648
It became an obligation
to me to preserve everything.

26:16.742 --> 26:20.803
And we've never sold one
bit of artifacts or treasure.

26:20.821 --> 26:22.471
We've kept it all intact.

26:22.564 --> 26:25.324
You know, we have
a big, big job ahead of us.

26:25.476 --> 26:28.252
These stories have to be
told with integrity.

26:28.403 --> 26:30.588
When's the last time you saw
a bag of pirate treasure?

26:30.739 --> 26:32.923
-Nobody's seen it.
-They don't.

26:33.075 --> 26:36.743
-This is the world's only
documented pirate treasure.
-Matty: Wow.

26:36.762 --> 26:38.596
